            ">Conclave begins</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/cardinals-take-oaths-sistine-chapel-pope-conclave-begins.png" alt="Cardinals from around the world line up in the Vatican's Sistine Chapel to take their oaths at the beginning of the conclave to elect a successor to Pope" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>
          Cardinals from around the world line up in the Vatican's Sistine Chapel to take their oaths at the beginning of the conclave to elect a successor to Pope. Credits: CNS photo/Vatican Media
            </i></p>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          The Catholic Church’s largest and most uncertain <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-7-may-25-spotlight-h1-1-conclave-begins?source=website" target="_blank">conclave begins</a> in the Sistine Chapel. With 133 cardinals from around the world participating, a two-thirds majority is required to elect the next pope. Voting will take place twice daily until one candidate prevails, signaled by the white smoke rising from the Apostolic Palace, and the next pope emerging onto the balcony. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         The church remains divided between progressives and traditionalists who <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-7-may-25-spotlight-h1-2-oppose-reforms?source=website" target="_blank">oppose reforms</a> like same-sex marriage, communion for divorcees, and decentralising authority, accepting other liturgy practices, not just the Latin mass. The electors have received a dossier on <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-7-may-25-spotlight-h1-3-40-candidates?source=website" target="_blank">40 candidates</a>, with around 20 seen as <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-7-may-25-spotlight-h1-4-potential-contenders?source=website" target="_blank">potential contenders</a>. The conclave is expected to last three to four days, though the last two concluded by the end of the second day. If three full days pass without resolution, they’ll pause for a day of reflection.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
          Currently sequestered in Casa Santa Maria, the cardinals will surrender their mobile phones and any contact with the outside world. They’ll be cloistered until a decision is made, traveling to the Sistine Chapel for their ballots.</p>
        </mj-text>
